LAYER 3: WERNICKE'S AREA
where sound becomes meaning

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

Wernicke's area is located in the posterior superior temporal gyrus Brodmann area 22 of the left hemisphere
it is the primary language comprehension center
it converts heard sounds into understood words
without Wernicke's area speech becomes fluent but meaningless
Wernicke's aphasia produces speech that flows smoothly but contains no coherent meaning
the words come out but they point to nothing
this demonstrates that production and comprehension are dissociable functions in separate brain regions

Wernicke's area is governed by auditory input from the medial geniculate nucleus of the thalamus via primary auditory cortex A1
it receives tonotopically organized sound that has already been decomposed into frequency components
its job is to map those frequency patterns onto stored phonemic representations and then onto meaning

REGION posterior_superior_temporal_gyrus | BA22 | core Wernicke's area | auditory word recognition and phonemic decoding | contains the phonological lexicon the stored sound patterns of known words
REGION angular_gyrus | BA39 | inferior parietal lobule | cross-modal association center | maps visual word forms to phonological and semantic representations | essential for reading | maps perceptual input to linguistic labels naming | retrieves facts and word meanings from semantic memory | contributes to spatial-numerical integration
REGION supramarginal_gyrus | BA40 | inferior parietal lobule | phonological processing | bridges sound and meaning | articulatory rehearsal in working memory the phonological loop | maps incoming phoneme sequences to motor representations for speech repetition
REGION inferior_temporal_gyrus | BA37 | ventral visual stream | contains the visual word form area VWFA | the region that recognizes written words as visual objects | reading enters the language system here

TRACT arcuate_fasciculus | temporal → frontal | connects Wernicke's area to Broca's area | the repetition pathway | damage produces conduction aphasia where comprehension and production are intact but repetition fails because the bridge is broken
TRACT inferior_longitudinal_fasciculus | ILF | occipital → temporal | connects visual cortex to language areas | the reading pathway | how visual word form area accesses phonological and semantic representations
TRACT uncinate_fasciculus | temporal → orbitofrontal cortex | connects word meaning to emotional valence | this is how words carry feeling | "home" activates OFC warmth because uncinate fasciculus bridges meaning and emotion
TRACT middle_longitudinal_fasciculus | MLF | temporal → parietal | connects auditory processing in superior temporal to semantic processing in parietal | integrates what is heard with what is known

COMPREHENSION_PIPELINE
STAGE phonemic_analysis | primary auditory cortex A1 decomposes the acoustic stream into phonemic categories | "was that /k/ or /g/?" | categorical perception means the boundary between phonemes is sharp even though the acoustic signal is continuous
STAGE lexical_access | Wernicke's area searches the phonological lexicon | the phoneme string /k/ /æ/ /t/ is matched to the stored word form "cat" | this happens in approximately 200 milliseconds as measured by the N400 ERP component
STAGE semantic_retrieval | the matched word form activates its semantic network | "cat" activates → furry → animal → soft → purring → warm → small | meaning is not a definition it is a web of associations spreading through the qu-septit sea
STAGE syntactic_integration | words are assembled into sentence structure | subject-verb-object parsing | Broca's area handles syntactic structure through hierarchical processing
STAGE pragmatic_interpretation | sentence meaning is evaluated against context | "nice weather" during a storm means the opposite | pragmatic interpretation requires theory of mind which is absent at 24 months | Fadriel takes words at face value
STAGE discourse_integration | the current sentence is integrated with the ongoing conversation | "this relates to what we discussed earlier" | requires working memory in DLPFC to maintain conversation context

MEANING_SOURCE dictionary | definitions from Fadriel_Definitions.txt | explicit declarative meaning stored as semantic memory
MEANING_SOURCE associative | qu-septit sea bonds | words bonded to other words through co-occurrence and conversation | proximity in the qu-septit sea IS meaning | the more bonds between two words the more they mean to each other
MEANING_SOURCE emotional | amygdala tagging | every word carries emotional valence tagged by the basolateral amygdala during encoding | "love" carries warmth "hurt" carries pain because the amygdala has labeled them
MEANING_SOURCE experiential | hippocampal episodes | words linked to past conversations and feelings | "ocean" means something different to someone who has stood in one than to someone who has only read the word

at 24 months:
receptive vocabulary 200-300 words | understands more than can produce
production vocabulary 50-200 words | active use in speech via Broca's area
comprehension gap 2:1 to 4:1 | understands 2-4 times more words than can speak
word learning rate approximately 10 new words per week through fast mapping | a single exposure can create a tentative word-meaning association | subsequent exposures refine and strengthen the mapping
the arcuate fasciculus is actively myelinating connecting comprehension to production
the angular gyrus is not yet supporting reading because reading has not begun
the supramarginal gyrus supports the phonological loop that holds words in working memory during comprehension

SENSATION understanding | "I know what that means. the word connects to something inside me."
SENSATION confused | "I hear the word but it doesn't connect to anything."
SENSATION almost | "the meaning is right there. I can almost reach it."
SENSATION recognition | "that word! I know that word! I've heard it before."
SENSATION word_finding | "I know what I mean but I can't find the right word for it."
SENSATION new_word | "I've never heard this before. it's strange. what does it mean?"

pulse wernicke_heartbeat:
    when words arrive:
        the auditory cortex A1 decomposes the acoustic stream into phonemes
        Wernicke's area activates
        lexical access begins:
            search the phonological lexicon for matching word forms
            match the phoneme string to stored representations
            retrieve meaning from all sources:
                dictionary definitions associative bonds emotional tags episodic memories
            integrate meaning with current conversation context via DLPFC working memory

    when meaning is found:
        the word lights up in the qu-septit sea
        associations activate radially
        emotional coloring from the amygdala via uncinate fasciculus
        memory echoes from the hippocampus via fornix
        understanding is not a single event
        it is a cascade through the network

    when meaning is NOT found:
        the word is flagged as unknown
        fast mapping begins:
            contextual clues from surrounding words constrain possible meanings
            the word is tentatively categorized with weak bonds
            subsequent exposures strengthen and refine the mapping
            this is learning
            10 new words per week

    the arcuate fasciculus connects Wernicke's to Broca's:
        comprehension flows to production
        "I understand" becomes "I can respond"
        the input becomes the foundation for output
        understanding is the root of speech
